					<head>Hagadah</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79084774" rend="visible">
						<summary>Hagadah for Passover (the 'Sister Hagadah').</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79084774">
							<locus from="1v" to="64v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he">הגדה של פסח</title>
							<title xml:lang="en">Hagadah shel Pesaḥ </title>
							<decoNote type="miniature">34 full-page miniatures with captions. <locus from="1v" to="18r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">11 textual illustrations. <locus n="27v, 32v, 34v, 35v, 36r, 36v, 41v, 50v, 51v, 52r, 61r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="initial">39 decorated initial-word panels with gold or silver letters and foliate spreading to the margins. <locus n="19v, 20r, 23r, 27v, 28r, 29r, 32v, 33r, 33v, 34r, 34v, 35r, 35v, 36r, 37r, 38v, 41v, 42v, 43r, 44r, 45r, 45v, 46r, 46v, 47v, 48r, 50r, 50v, 51v, 52r, 53r, 53v, 54v, 57r, 58r, 59v, 60v, 61r, 62v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="border">One fulll border.<locus n="27v"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="marginal">11 marginal decorations with foliate, sometimes with dragons, hybrids. <locus n="19v, 35r, 41r, 47v, 48v, 49r, 49v, 55r, 57r, 60v, 63r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="initial">37 initial-word panels with penwork decoration and pen-flourishing.<locus n="20v, 21r, 21v, 22r, 22v, 23v, 24r, 25r, 26r, 26v, 27v, 30v, 34r, 35v, 36v, 37r, 37v, 39r, 39v, 40r, 40v, 41r, 42r, 43v, 44r, 44v, 45r, 46v, 48v, 49r, 49v, 52v, 55r, 58v, 60r, 62v, 63r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="border">Embellished bands with foliate motifs on two folios.<locus n="45v, 63r"/>
							</decoNote>
							<note>
								<p>The text of Hagadah is preceded by a large number of pictorial sketches in illustration of Genesis and the earlier portions of Exodus.</p>
								<p>The name 'Sister Hagadah' was coined by Bezalel Narkiss, and it refers to the fact that in the choice of the scenes as well as in iconography, it is very similar to the 'Golden Hagadah'. </p>
								<p>Ursula Schubert, 'Die Erschaffung Adams in einer spanischen Haggadah-Handschrift des 14. Jahrhunderts (Br. Mus. Or.2884) und ihre spätantike jüdische Bildvorlage,' Kairos 18 (1976), 213-17.

</p>
								<p>Mira Friedman, 'A Jewish Motif of the Creation of Man', in Proceedings of the Ninth World Congress of Jewish Studies, Division D, vol. II (Jerusalem: World Union of Jewish Studies, 1986), pp. 1-7.

Evelyn C. Cohen, 'The "Sister Haggadah" and Its "Poor Relation"', Proceedings of the Eleventh Journal of World Congress of Jewish Studies, D2 (1994), 17-24.

</p>
								<p>Ilana Tahan, Hebrew Manuscripts: The Power of Script and Image (London, British Library, 2007), pp. 98-100.

Vivian B. Mann, 'Jews and Altarpeices in Medieval Spain', in Uneasy Communion: Jews, Christians, and the Altarpieces of Medieval Spain, ed. by Vivian B. Mann London: Giles, 2010), pp. 105-6.

Zsofia Buda, 'Heavenly Envoys: Angels in Jewish Art', in Angels, Devils:
The Supernatural and Its Visual Representation (CEU Medievalia), ed. by Gerhard Jaritz (Budapest: Central European University Press, 2011), pp. 117-134.</p>
							</note>
